---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Music" currentPage="music">
  <h1 class="page-title">My Music</h1>
  <p class="page-subtitle">
    Not that kind of music. This is an archive of my guiding principles — the ideas that are true regardless of my circumstances.
  </p>

  <!-- Origin Story -->
  <div class="music-origin">
    <p class="music-prose">
      When I was finishing up a mission for <a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints</a>, I was listening to a sermon when I heard this phrase:
    </p>
    <blockquote class="music-blockquote">
      "Don't die with your music still in you."
    </blockquote>
    <div class="music-video">
      <iframe
        width="100%"
        height="400"
        src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/fJH2xgLMkPg"
        title="The Power of the Priesthood in the Boy"
        frameborder="0"
        allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"
        allowfullscreen
        style="border-radius: var(--radius);"
      ></iframe>
    </div>
    <p class="music-prose">
      That phrase has always stuck with me no matter what experience is taking up the focus of my life. I walked away from that with an intense desire to take what I've learned and make sure it gets heard. Not just for me to make sure I get my moment, but to leave what I've learned to future generations.
    </p>
    <p class="music-prose">
      This page is an opportunity for me to look back at the times when I've captured "my music," the things I want to leave behind for others. This is also an archive for me to capture the ideas that are true regardless of my circumstances. My guiding principles.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="section-divider"></div>

  <!-- My Principles -->
  <h2 class="section-heading">My Principles</h2>
  <div class="section-divider"></div>

  <!-- Principle 1 -->
  <div class="principle-card">
    <div class="principle-quote">"Whatever you are, be a good one."</div>
    <div class="principle-attribution">— Abraham Lincoln</div>
    <p class="principle-context">
      The first time I heard this was actually in <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jQB_zhddfFg" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">a joke by Mike Birbiglia</a> <em>specifically</em> pointing out how it was a stupid quote. But the more I've thought about it, the more it resonates with me. I don't want to be the person who has biased expectations of what people should or shouldn't be. Whatever you want to be, you should strive to excel at that thing and become the very best you can.
    </p>
    <a class="tweet-card" href="https://x.com/MrBeast/status/1768431267505213672" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
      <div class="tweet-header">
        <div class="tweet-avatar">🟣</div>
        <div class="tweet-user">
          <span class="tweet-name">MrBeast</span>
          <span class="tweet-handle">@MrBeast</span>
        </div>
        <svg class="tweet-x-logo" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z" fill="currentColor"/></svg>
      </div>
      <p class="tweet-text">It's painful to see people quit their job/drop out of school to make content full time before they're ready. For every person like me that makes it, thousands don't. Keep that in mind and be smart plz</p>
      <span class="tweet-date">5:17 PM · Mar 14, 2024</span>
    </a>
  </div>

  <!-- Principle 2 -->
  <div class="principle-card">
    <div class="principle-quote">"Don't rain on somebody's hustle."</div>
    <div class="principle-attribution">— Alex Spencer</div>
    <p class="principle-context">
      I wrote an article called <a href="/essays/building-customer-love">Is The Lean Startup a Stupid Way to Start a Company?</a> where I critiqued a book that I disagreed with. A friend of mine, Alex Spencer, mentioned that he didn't disagree with me, but that he tried never to "rain on someone's hustle" when they're working hard towards something. Interesting debate between constructive criticism vs. "raining on someone's hustle."
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Principle 3 -->
  <div class="principle-card">
    <div class="principle-quote">"You don't have to blow out the other person's candle to let your own shine."</div>
    <div class="principle-attribution">— Larry H. Miller</div>
    <p class="principle-context">
      First read this in Larry H. Miller's autobiography, <em>Driven</em>. Similar to the one above, but it goes deeper into the "why" behind not feeling like life is a zero sum game. Much of life is, in fact, a non-zero sum game. Something I've <a href="/essays/the-non-zero-sum-game-of-ambition">written about before</a>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Principle 4 -->
  <div class="principle-card">
    <div class="principle-quote">"Prepare for the worst, and expect the best to come from it."</div>
    <div class="principle-attribution">— Lori Harrison</div>
    <p class="principle-context">
      When I was a senior in high school I ran for Student Body President. My Mom helped me work hard to prepare, to campaign, to talk with people, and position myself well. The result of the election was going to be announced in a big assembly in front of the whole school. My Mom told me that if I lost, I could just slip out the back and we could go to lunch. That wasn't a lack of faith in my ability to win. It was a conscious decision to understand all the possible outcomes and put in place a good plan.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="music-blockquote" style="margin-top: 16px;">
      "Anticipating problems and figuring out how to solve them is actually the opposite of worrying: it's productive."
      <span class="blockquote-attr">— Chris Hadfield</span>
    </blockquote>
    <a class="tweet-card" href="https://x.com/paulg/status/1376078468681715712" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
      <div class="tweet-header">
        <div class="tweet-avatar">🟠</div>
        <div class="tweet-user">
          <span class="tweet-name">Paul Graham</span>
          <span class="tweet-handle">@paulg</span>
        </div>
        <svg class="tweet-x-logo" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z" fill="currentColor"/></svg>
      </div>
      <p class="tweet-text">"Hope for the best and plan for the worst" is a good principle but a bit too passive for startup founders. For founders it should be more like "Try for the best but be prepared for the worst that can happen en route."</p>
      <span class="tweet-date">12:47 AM · Mar 28, 2021</span>
    </a>
  </div>

  <!-- Principle 5 -->
  <div class="principle-card">
    <div class="principle-quote">"Don't look for a partner in someone who completes you or who needs you to complete them. Be two complete people who love being around each other."</div>
    <div class="principle-attribution">— Lori Harrison</div>
    <p class="principle-context">
      I have seen this be true both in finding a spouse and in working relationships.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Principle 6 -->
  <div class="principle-card">
    <div class="principle-quote">"Don't look to complain. Look to improve."</div>
    <div class="principle-attribution">— Clint Topham</div>
    <a class="tweet-card" href="https://x.com/Austen/status/1379937235022225408" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
      <div class="tweet-header"><div class="tweet-avatar">🔵</div><div class="tweet-user"><span class="tweet-name">Austen Allred</span><span class="tweet-handle">@Austen</span></div><svg class="tweet-x-logo" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z" fill="currentColor"/></svg></div>
      <p class="tweet-text">Saying, "We need to get rid of x; it's bad" is very easy.

Coming up with a superior replacement for x is usually incredibly difficult.</p>
      <span class="tweet-date">4:20 PM · Apr 7, 2021</span>
    </a>
    <a class="tweet-card" href="https://x.com/BrentBeshore/status/1688881144865886208" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
      <div class="tweet-header"><div class="tweet-avatar">🟢</div><div class="tweet-user"><span class="tweet-name">Brent Beshore</span><span class="tweet-handle">@BrentBeshore</span></div><svg class="tweet-x-logo" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z" fill="currentColor"/></svg></div>
      <p class="tweet-text">C Players: "This is broken. Someone should fix it."

B Players: "This is broken. Do you want me to start working on fixing it?"

A Players: "This broke. I fixed it, recruited someone to be responsible for it, and created a process for others to more easily fix it in the future."</p>
      <span class="tweet-date">4:53 AM · Aug 8, 2023</span>
    </a>
    <a class="tweet-card" href="https://x.com/terronk/status/1683940737451454464" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
      <div class="tweet-header"><div class="tweet-avatar">🟤</div><div class="tweet-user"><span class="tweet-name">Lee Edwards</span><span class="tweet-handle">@terronk</span></div><svg class="tweet-x-logo" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z" fill="currentColor"/></svg></div>
      <p class="tweet-text">Me: Here's an idea.
Dumbass: What about this downside/cost?
M: That's real. Do you think it's worse than the upside?
DA: No
M: Do you have an alternative?
DA: No
M: Does the problem need a solution?
DA: Yes
M: …

There needs to be a word for this particular kind of stfu.</p>
      <span class="tweet-date">1:42 PM · Jul 25, 2023</span>
    </a>
    <a class="tweet-card" href="https://x.com/ValaAfshar/status/1808166096752586894" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
      <div class="tweet-header"><div class="tweet-avatar">⚪</div><div class="tweet-user"><span class="tweet-name">Vala Afshar</span><span class="tweet-handle">@ValaAfshar</span></div><svg class="tweet-x-logo" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z" fill="currentColor"/></svg></div>
      <p class="tweet-text">Complaining is not a strategy.</p>
      <span class="tweet-date">8:49 AM · Jul 2, 2024</span>
    </a>
  </div>

  <!-- Principle 7 -->
  <div class="principle-card">
    <div class="principle-quote">"How many times have you done it? If it isn't millions, it isn't enough."</div>
    <div class="principle-attribution">— Dax Harrison</div>
    <p class="principle-context">
      When I talk to my kids, we often talk about how many times you have to try something before you get good at it. Dax settled on the number "millions," so that's how we stay resilient.
    </p>
    <a class="tweet-card" href="https://x.com/visakanv/status/1330984685992722433" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
      <div class="tweet-header"><div class="tweet-avatar">🟡</div><div class="tweet-user"><span class="tweet-name">Visakan Veerasamy</span><span class="tweet-handle">@visakanv</span></div><svg class="tweet-x-logo" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z" fill="currentColor"/></svg></div>
      <p class="tweet-text">1. Do it 100 times.

Write 100 songs, cook 100 omelettes, talk to 100 people. It never seems like a huge deal until you try it yourself. It's manageable, and yet it stretches you, and you'll be observably different at the end of it.

Effective way to get a foothold on a new thing</p>
      <span class="tweet-date">1:24 PM · Nov 23, 2020</span>
    </a>
  </div>

  <div class="section-divider" style="margin-top: 40px;"></div>

  <!-- Greatest Hits -->
  <h2 class="section-heading">My Music: The Greatest Hits</h2>
  <div class="section-divider"></div>

  <!-- Mission Carousel -->
  <div class="hits-collection">
    <h3 class="hits-collection-title">At the end of my mission for The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints</h3>
    <p class="hits-collection-intro">
      In General Conference April 2013, Elder Tad R. Callister of the Seventy said, "Do not die with your music still in you." The last six months of my mission I felt great gratitude for the growth I experienced. It is my desire to record the greatest lessons I learned — most from the missionaries I served with or near.
    </p>

    <div class="carousel" id="mission-carousel">
      <div class="carousel-viewport">
        <div class="carousel-track" id="mission-track">

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">01</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Meetings, programs, plans etc. are as important as you make them. If you treat something like it's no big deal then so will they. If it's important to you it will be important to them.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">When we tried to re-evaluate the ward mission plan in Altoona, Bishop Cross made it "not a big deal" and instead of talking about it in ward council he just wanted to pass around copies in the hallway.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">02</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Don't look at something you do and say "this is stupid, let's not do it." Instead, look at what you do and ask, "this is not as effective as it should be; how can we make it better?"</p>
            <p class="slide-context">Elder Collier said, "be advised that using that as a measuring device is a tool, and in not using them you're not using a tool that the General Authorities have said is important."</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">03</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">The future is as bright as your faith. Sometimes you'll try something; it will work brilliantly. The next time you try it, it blows up in your face. Often times God makes something a little harder each time so you can really think about the details.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">In Wintersville they shot me down when I tried to redo the area book. Then in Altoona, Elder Neuder taught me that I need to have faith even if other people don't.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">04</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">We invite others to come unto Christ, not just non-members. If you don't believe that people can change then you'll be right 99% of the time.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">Elder Bradley Nilsen said this in a zone conference.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">05</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Writing things down is important. Revelation left unrecorded is unappreciated. How you record things is not as important as the fact that you record it.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">I came up with this when I read a talk by Richard G. Scott about journals.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">06</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Routine is the murderer of missionary work. If you're doing something because that's how it's always been done then you're standing in the way of progression. Evaluate and grow.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">Elder Brady said this but I applied it to something I had learned about missionaries who do things because that's just how it's always been done.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">07</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">If your primary focus is your relationship with them then you are damaging their future progress. If your primary focus is their future progress you will have an unbreakable relationship with them.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">I learned this coming to Freeport — the missionaries had been more worried about their relationship with people than about their progression.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">08</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Talking with everyone is never not awkward. If you try to make it cool you just look silly AND awkward. If you embrace that it's awkward and that it's necessary then it becomes fun.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">I would say this every time I went on exchange with a young missionary as a Zone Leader because they were always surprised by how awkward it is.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">09</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">If your mission is the best two years of your life ten years from now then you're not married, you don't have children and you're not active in the church. If the MTC is the best two weeks of your mission then you're doing something wrong.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">Elder Kenley said this in my last zone conference and then Elder Packard came up with the part at the end about the MTC.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">10</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">No experience, for bad or for good, is a waste if you learn from it.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">Elder Leavitt lamented about all the time he had wasted being disobedient and this, by revelation, is what I told him.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">11</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">We're not in the good lesson business, or the good OYM business. We're in the good people business. This work isn't about building areas it's about building you.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">I said this frequently to Elder Curl when he wanted me to just talk to people instead of him.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">12</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Meaningful service is not measured by the amount of physical exertion, it's measured by how much you actually want to help. It's not loading up a barrel of apples to impress your mom, it's caring enough to want to make your companion's bed.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">This story happened back home when I was trying to get out of being grounded. I filled up a big barrel of apples and Mom pointed out how that didn't help her at all.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">13</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">No matter how many times you go fishing you won't keep your catch if your net is broken. No matter how many people you baptize, never leave an area without helping them become more effective.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">President Hinckley said this in his talk, "Find the Lambs, Feed the Sheep." I've always felt this way about missionary work.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">14</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Remember the last time you messed up. What happened the next morning? You woke up. Remember the last time your performance was outstanding. What happened the next morning? You woke up. Don't stop the future from constantly being better.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">I said this in a district meeting in Ephrata when the district members were being pretty hard on themselves.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">15</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Righteous seekers of truth think "I just need to be better." Those who study the Atonement think "I can try to be better." Those who understand and apply the Atonement declare, "I can be better."</p>
            <p class="slide-context">"I just need to be better" was my catchphrase with Elder Christensen. As my understanding grew, my idea became this phrase.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">16</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Prepare for the worst; expect the best to come. In every situation prepare yourself for the worst case scenario; then, move forward exercising faith, expecting the best no matter the outcome.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">Mom told me this when I ran for Student Body President. It transformed into a real solid statement regarding faith throughout my mission.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">17</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">If you want something you've never had you have to do something you've never done.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">Elder Collier said this during one of our first companionship studies in Altoona.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">18</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Studying for your investigators does not mean you ignore what comes to your mind in order to focus on a lesson plan. Studying for your investigators means you try to figure out how the things that come to your mind apply to them.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">David O. McKay said "you tell me what you think about when you don't have to think and I'll tell you what you are."</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">19</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">The greatest missionary is a thief. If you're constantly trying to learn from other missionaries you'll never be stagnant. The Lord has blessed others for your benefit. Be teachable. Be an idea sponge.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">Elder Bradley Nilsen said this when he came on exchange with me and Elder Curl.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="carousel-slide">
            <div class="slide-number">20</div>
            <p class="slide-lesson">Doing a good deed daily is like peeing your pants. Everybody can see what you've done but only you can feel the warmth.</p>
            <p class="slide-context">The Stake Young Men's President in the York Stake said this. I thought it was funny.</p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="carousel-controls">
        <button class="carousel-btn" id="mission-prev" aria-label="Previous slide">&#8592;</button>
        <span class="carousel-counter" id="mission-counter">1 / 20</span>
        <button class="carousel-btn" id="mission-next" aria-label="Next slide">&#8594;</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<script is:inline>
  function initCarousel(id) {
    const track = document.getElementById(id + '-track');
    const counter = document.getElementById(id + '-counter');
    const prevBtn = document.getElementById(id + '-prev');
    const nextBtn = document.getElementById(id + '-next');
    if (!track) return;
    const slides = track.querySelectorAll('.carousel-slide');
    const total = slides.length;
    let current = 0;
    function update() {
      track.style.transform = 'translateX(-' + (current * 100) + '%)';
      counter.textContent = (current + 1) + ' / ' + total;
      prevBtn.disabled = current === 0;
      nextBtn.disabled = current === total - 1;
    }
    prevBtn.addEventListener('click', function() { if (current > 0) { current--; update(); } });
    nextBtn.addEventListener('click', function() { if (current < total - 1) { current++; update(); } });
    let startX = 0;
    track.addEventListener('touchstart', function(e) { startX = e.touches[0].clientX; }, { passive: true });
    track.addEventListener('touchend', function(e) {
      var diff = startX - e.changedTouches[0].clientX;
      if (diff > 50 && current < total - 1) { current++; update(); }
      if (diff < -50 && current > 0) { current--; update(); }
    }, { passive: true });
    update();
  }
  initCarousel('mission');
</script>

<style>
  .music-prose {
    font-size: 15px;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .music-prose a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  .music-blockquote {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 12px 20px;
    margin: 20px 0;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 20px;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  .blockquote-attr {
    display: block;
    font-size: 14px;
    font-style: normal;
    color: var(--text-tertiary);
    margin-top: 8px;
    font-family: var(--font-body);
  }
  .music-video {
    margin: 24px 0;
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .music-video iframe { display: block; }
  .principle-card {
    padding: 24px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .principle-card:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .principle-quote {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 19px;
    font-weight: 500;
